\begin_layout Section*
Definition of the range of interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we want to understand the potential ecological consequences of phytoplankton
 aggregation, we define a range of distances from a particle where interactions
 with other particles are possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The smallest physically possible distance is equal to the sum of the radius
 of interacting particles (which would be equal to 1 diameter as we consider
 particles of the same size within one simulation).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The higher range of distances depend on the modeled interaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Competition for nutrients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we consider competition for nutrients as one of the main interactions
 between particles, we can define the volume of depletion around a particle
 as the volume where the nutrient concentration is decreased by the particle
 uptake.
 A usual threshold is the 90% concentration decrease corresponding to a
 sphere of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C(r)\leq90\%C_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\infty}$
\end_inset

