\begin_layout Section*
Points or spheres?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For now, the Brownian Bug Model deals with points, i.e.
 particles which do not have a physical size and can aggregate at very small
 scales: distance between points can be close, if not equal, to 0 while
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

physical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 minimum distance between particles should be equal to the sum of their
 radius.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest solution which was proposed to partly counteract this unrealistic
 aggregation was to place a child particle at a distance equal to 1 diameter
 from the parent when birth happens.
 This would at least avoid aggregation simply due to reproduction placement.
 However, we prove that it is not necessary as one time step is enough to
 separate them by more than a diameter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed, if we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $s(t)$
\end_inset

 the separation between two particles, it should follow an exponentiel increase
 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
s(t) & = & s_{0}e^{\gamma t}\\
\Leftrightarrow & t= & \frac{1}{\gamma}\log\left(\frac{s(t)}{s_{0}}\right)
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in Young et al.
 2001 (which is a specific simulation, not what seems to be done in the
 rest of the article), 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}=10^{-7}$
\end_inset

.
 We take 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\approx0.5$
\end_inset

 and consider the largest separation between particles, that is the diameter
 of a diatom (
\begin_inset Formula $50\times10^{-6}$
\end_inset

 m).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=\frac{1}{0.5}\log\left(\frac{50\times10^{-6}}{10^{-7}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $t=12$
\end_inset

 s, below 
\begin_inset Formula $t=16$
\end_inset

 s which has previously been fixed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it should be noted that this corresponds to a case where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}=10^{-7}$
\end_inset

.
 In the present model, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 While we do not need to separate daughter and parent by one diameter, we
 may still need to separate them even by a small distance at birth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be noted that in a 3D, individual-based model with diffusion and
 turbulence (with a comparison of direct numerical simulations of the Navier-Sto
kes equations and Kraichnan simulations) for motile organisms, Breier et
 al.
 (2018) find that replacing point particles by solid spheres does not change
 the qualitative results.
 
\end_layout

